title._content: Workers finish donning SCAPE suits for the fueling of the Comet Nucleus Tour (CONTOUR) spacecraft

description._content: Collection: NASA Kennedy Center Media Archive Collection Description: KENNEDY SPACE CENTER, FLA. -- Workers finish donning SCAPE suits for the fueling of the Comet Nucleus Tour (CONTOUR) spacecraft in the Spacecraft Assembly and Encapsulation Facility 2 (SAEF-2). SCAPE refers to Self-Contained Atmospheric Protective Ensemble. CONTOUR will provide the first detailed look into the heart of a comet -- the nucleus. Flying as close as 60 miles (100 kilometers) to at least two comets, the spacecraft will take the sharpest pictures yet of a nucleus while analyzing the gas and dust that surround them. CONTOUR is scheduled for launch aboard a Boeing Delta II rocket July 1, 2002, from Launch Complex 17-A, Cape Canaveral Air Force Station Release Date: 06/06/2002 Photo Number: KSC-02PD-0958 UID: SPD-KSCMA-KSC-02PD-0 958 original url: mediaarchive.ksc.nasa.gov/detail.cfm?mediaid=9852 SOURCE: nasaimages.org/luna/servlet/detail/nasaNAS~6~6~29997~133860 Visit www.nasaimages.org for the most comprehensive compilation of NASA stills, film and video, created in partnership with Internet Archive.
